a-La Mancha, Španjolska","Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Španjolska","España":"Španjolska"},"cs":{"1261–1288":"1261–1288","1257–1288":"1257–1288","1282–Female":"1282–Zesnulá","1284–1330":"1284–1330","1284–Male":"1284–Zesnulý","1290–Female":"1290–Zesnulá","–Male":"Zesnulý","–Female":"Zesnulá","ABT 1284":"okolo 1284","1257":"1257","1288":"1288","1330":"1330","1284":"1284","1261":"1261","1282":"1282","1290":"1290","Toledo, Nueva Castilla, España":"New Castile, Španělsko","Toledo, New Castile, Spain":"Diócesis de Toledo, Španělsko","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Španělsko","Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Španělsko","España":"Španělsko"},"da":{"1261–1288":"1261–1288","1257–1288":"1257–1288","1282–Female":"1282–Afdød","1284–1330":"1284–1330","1284–Male":"1284–Afdød","1290–Female":"1290–Afdød","–Male":"Afdød","–Female":"Afdød","ABT 1284":"omkring 1284","1257":"1257","1288":"1288","1330":"1330","1284":"1284","1261":"1261","1282":"1282","1290":"1290","Toledo, Nueva Castilla, España":"New Castile, Spanien","Toledo, New Castile, Spain":"Diócesis de Toledo, Spanien","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spanien","Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spanien","España":"Spanien"},"nl":{"1261–1288":"1261–1288","1257–1288":"1257–1288","1282–Female":"1282–Overleden","1284–1330":"1284–1330","1284–Male":"1284–Overleden","1290–Female":"1290–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","ABT 1284":"circa 1284","1257":"1257","1288":"1288","1330":"1330","1284":"1284","1261":"1261","1282":"1282","1290":"1290","Toledo, Nueva Castilla, España":"New Castile, Spanje","Toledo, New Castile, Spain":"Diócesis de Toledo, Spanje","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spanje","Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spanje","España":"Spanje"},"en":{"1261–1288":"1261–1288","1257–1288":"1257–1288","1282–Female":"1282–Deceased","1284–1330":"1284–1330","1284–Male":"1284–Deceased","1290–Female":"1290–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","ABT 1284":"about 1284","1257":"1257","1288":"1288","1330":"1330","1284":"1284","1261":"1261","1282":"1282","1290":"1290","Toledo, Nueva Castilla, España":"New Castile, Spain","Toledo, New Castile, Spain":"Diócesis de Toledo, Spain","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, España":"Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","España":"Spain","nameMeanings":[{"name":"García","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jesus, Carlos, Luis, Francisco, Pedro, Miguel, Jorge, Mario, Raul, Roberto, Ramon, Rafael.  Portuguese Wenceslao, Joao, Paulo, Catarina, Albeiro, Ligia, Godofredo, Lidio, Wenseslao, Adao, Afonso.","Spanish (<b>García</b>) and Portuguese: from a medieval personal name of uncertain origin. It is normally found in medieval records in the Latin form <i>Garsea</i>, and may well be of pre-Roman origin, perhaps akin to Basque <i>(h)artz</i> ‘bear’. This is the most common surname in Spain and also one of the most common surnames elsewhere in Spanish-speaking world. In the US, where it is also found among Native Americans (mainly Pueblos in NM), it is the sixth most frequent surname. Compare   De Garcia  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Grassia","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Amedeo, Maurizio, Pasquale, Rocco, Salvatore.","Italian: from a metathesized form of the personal name<i>Garsia</i>, from Spanish <i>García</i> (see   Garcia  )."]},{"name":"Arcia","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Alberto, Francisco, Arturo, Dagoberto, Enrique, Jose, Ramiro, Adalberto, Aleida, Alejandro, Alfredo, Amalia.","Hispanic: probably an altered form of Spanish <b>García</b> (see   Garcia  )."]},{"name":"Garcie","meanings":["Altered form, under the French influence in LA, of Spanish <b>García</b> (see   Garcia  ). This form of the surname of Spanish origin is also found in southern France.","Spanish (Ávila): variant of <b>García</b> (see   Garcia  )."]},{"name":"Garcilazo","meanings":["Hispanic (mainly Mexico and Argentina): altered form of Spanish (Valencia) <b>Garcilaso</b>, a compound of the personal name <i>Garci</i> (a short form of <i>García</i>, see   Garcia  ) and the nickname <i>laso</i> ‘weak, exhausted’."]},{"name":"Gacia","meanings":["Hispanic: altered form of Spanish <b>García</b> (see   Garcia  )."]},{"name":"Garsia","meanings":["Hispanic: altered form of   Garcia  ."]},{"name":"Gracia","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Juan, Manuel, Francisco, Jesus, Luis, Guadalupe, Mario, Pedro, Javier, Jorge.","Spanish; Catalan (<b>Gràcia</b>): from a short form of the Christian religious epithet <i>de la Gracia</i>, meaning ‘of mercy’ and forming part of the Marian name <i>Maria de la Gracia</i> ‘(Holy) Mary of Grace’, from Spanish <i>gracia</i>, Catalan <i>gràcia</i> ‘grace, mercy’.","In some cases possibly also an altered form of Spanish <b>García</b> (see   Garcia  )."]},{"name":"De Garcia","meanings":["Spanish and Galician (<b>De García</b>); Portuguese: patronymic from Spanish and Galician <b>García</b> and Portuguese   Garcia  , with the preposition <i>de</i> ‘of’."]},{"name":"Garces","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jorge, Carlos, Juan, Jose, Manuel, Cesar, Rafael, Luis, Fernando, Gustavo, Javier, Mario.  Portuguese Albeiro, Paulo.","Spanish; Catalan (<b>Garcés</b>); Portuguese (<b>Garcês</b>): patronymic from the personal name <i>García</i> (see   Garcia  )."]},{"name":"Garzia","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Mario, Alfredo, Ernestina, Fernando, Juan, Pedro, Ricardo.  Italian Angelo, Antonio, Ciro, Corrado.","Italianized form of Spanish   Garcia  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Toledo","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Luis, Jorge, Manuel, Ramon, Rafael, Juan, Antonio, Jesus, Miguel, Roberto, Carlos, Francisco.","Spanish and Jewish (Sephardic): habitational name from the city in central Spain, which was the capital of the Visigothic state between the 6th and 8th centuries. Its role declined for three centuries after the Muslim invasion of Spain, until it was taken as the capital of the kingdom of Castile between the 11th and 16th centuries. It was a major cultural and political center throughout the Middle Ages, and was also the home of an important Jewish community. The placename, first recorded in Latin as <i>Toletum</i>, is of obscure etymology, possibly connected with <i>Toleto</i> in Piedmont; Jewish tradition connects it with Hebrew <i>toledot</i> ‘generations’, but this is no more than folk etymology. Compare   Toledano  .","Jewish (Sephardic): also an adoption of the Spanish surname (see 1 above) at the moment of conversion to Roman Catholicism. After the return to Judaism (generations later), some descendants retained the surname their families used as Catholics."],"variants":[{"name":"Toledano","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Shlomo, Igal, Moshe, Shimon, Ehud, Shmuel, Yehuda.  Spanish Alberto, Gonzalo, Alina, Carlos, Conrado, Elena, Enrique, Evelia, Luis, Manuel, Miguel, Ramona.  French Gabrielle, Michel.","Spanish and Jewish (Sephardic): habitational name for someone from Toledo (see   Toledo  ), from an adjectival form of the placename."]}]},{"name":"Inés","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Agnes  , now also used, usually without the accent, in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[{"name":"Agnes","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Inés García de Toledo was born in 1261, in Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain. She had at least 3 sons and 3 daughters with Juan Garcia de Toledo. She died in 1288, in Spain, at the age of 27."},"et":{"1261–1288":"1261–1288","1257–1288":"1257–1288","1282–Female":"1282–Surnud","1284–1330":"1284–1330","1284–Male":"1284–Surnud","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","ABT 1284":"umbes 1284","1257":"1257","1288":"1288","1330":"1330","1284":"1284","1261":"1261","1282":"1282","1290":"1290","Toledo, Nueva Castilla, España":"New Castile, Hispaania","Toledo, New Castile, Spain":"Diócesis de Toledo,